title: Moorend Common
text:
Moorend Common is a 28 hectare <a href="Site%20of%20Special%20Scientific%20Interest">Site of Special Scientific Interest</a> in the hamlet <a href="Lane%20End%2C%20Buckinghamshire">Moor End</a>, west of <a href="High%20Wycombe">High Wycombe</a> in <a href="Buckinghamshire">Buckinghamshire</a>. It is in the <a href="Chilterns">Chilterns</a> <a href="Areas%20of%20Outstanding%20Natural%20Beauty">Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty</a>, and it is owned and managed by Lane End Parish Council.
The site is on <a href="London%20Clay">London Clay</a>, which is unusual for the Chilterns, and the soil is acid and sometimes waterlogged. Habitats are grassland, heath, woodland, marsh and scrub. A stream ends in a <a href="swallow-hole">swallow-hole</a> called Gubbins Hole. There are three types of woodland, beech, oak and birch, and a small area planted with larch and pine, with ground flora of bracken and bramble. Marshy areas have <a href="heath%20spotted%20orchid">heath spotted orchid</a> and bog mosses.
There is access from Church Road, which passes through the site.
